SIMPLE: muriate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Muriate
<hw>Mu"ri*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Muriatic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of muriatic
hydrochloric acid; a chloride; <as>as, <ex>muriate</ex> of
ammonia</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This term, as also the word <xex>muriatic</xex>, was
formerly applied to the chlorides before their true composition was
understood, and while they were erroneously supposed to be compounds of
an acid with an oxide. <xex>Muriate</xex> and <xex>muriatic</xex> are
still occasionally used as commercial terms, but are obsolete in
scientific language.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muriated</ent>⟦br⟧
